Na$_{2}$PrO$_{3}$ can be found in three forms (Okuma, 2024): \begin{itemize} \item As \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B3C_mC48_15_aef_3f_2e-001}{monoclinic $\alpha$-Na$_{2}$PrO$_{3}$} (this structure), \item As orthorhombic $\beta$-Na$_{2}$PrO$_{3}$, in the \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B3C_oF96_70_2e_fh_e-001}{$\beta$-Na$_{2}$PtO$_{3}$ structure}, or \item As $\gamma$-Na$_{2}$PrO$_{3}$, in the \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B3C_oF96_70_2e_fh_e-001}{rock salt ($B1$) structure}, with the sodium and praseodymium mixed on the alkali site. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 (Hinatsu, 2006) found that the site we have labeled Na-II is actually 2/3 sodium and 1/3 praseodymium, statistically distributed, while the site we label Pr-I is 1/3 sodium and 2/3 praseodymium. 
 Some authors use Li$_{2}$SnO$_{3}$ as the prototype for this structure.
